{"title_page": "Barry Buckley", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2011}}\n'''Barry Buckley''' (1938\u20132006) was an Australian [[jazz]] double bassist and dental technician from [[Melbourne]], a notable presence on the modern jazz scene for over 40 years.<ref name=\"Vining\">{{cite web |last1=Vining |first1=Ted |title='Boss of bass' got his teeth stuck into jazz - Opinion - theage.com.au |url=https://www.theage.com.au/news/opinion/boss-of-bass-got-his-teeth-stuck-into-jazz/2006/09/26/1159036540759.html |website=www.theage.com.au |accessdate=3 July 2018 |language=en |date=27 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1950s Buckley joined pianist David Martin, trumpeter [[Keith Hounslow]], drummer [[Stewie Speer|Stewart Speer]] (later of Max Merritt fame) and saxophonist Brian Brown to form the first Brian Brown Quintet becoming Australia's foremost hard bop group, regularly playing  at [[Horst Liepolt]]'s ''Jazz Centre 44'' in St Kilda.\n\nLater Buckley teamed with drummer  [[Ted Vining]] and pianist [[Don Wilde]]  with Don Bennett as host to run the [[Cool Cats Show]] on Channel 7 for two years.\n\nFor several years in the early 1960s Buckley dropped out of the Jazz scene to establish Buckley-Hutton laboratories, which would become one of the biggest dental labs in the southern hemisphere, and to devote time to family.\n\nHe emerged in the late sixties teaming up with Brian Brown, Tony Gould and Ted Vining to form the Brian Brown Quartet. After a few years Gould left the group, replaced by a young [[Bob Sedergreen]]. Around 1969 the trio of Buckley, Sedergreen and Vining formed and played together  for the next 37 years. The Quartet disbanded in 1979 when Vining moved north to Sydney then Brisbane.\n\t\nIn the 1980s Buckley joined Martin Jackson (one of the founders of the [[Melbourne Jazz Co-operative]]) in his group Odwala and also participated in Sedergreen's Blues on the Boil, and performed with [[Bernie McGann]].\n\nBuckley's last performance was with the Ted Vining Trio at the North Coast Jazz Festival in Bangalow three months before his death from cancer in September 2006. Three days before his death Buckley donated an historic three-stringed DeVereaux double bass to the Museum of Victoria.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{jazzfooter|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buckley, Barry}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian jazz double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Male double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2011}}\n'''Barry Buckley''' (1938\u20132006) was an Australian [[jazz]] double bassist and dental technician from [[Melbourne]], a notable presence on the modern jazz scene for over 40 years.<ref name=\"Vining\">{{cite web |last1=Vining |first1=Ted |title='Boss of bass' got his teeth stuck into jazz - Opinion - theage.com.au |url=https://www.theage.com.au/news/opinion/boss-of-bass-got-his-teeth-stuck-into-jazz/2006/09/26/1159036540759.html |website=www.theage.com.au |accessdate=3 July 2018 |language=en |date=27 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1950s Buckley joined pianist David Martin, trumpeter [[Keith Hounslow]], drummer [[Stewie Speer|Stewart Speer]] (later of Max Merritt fame) and saxophonist Brian Brown to form the first Brian Brown Quintet becoming Australia's foremost hard bop group, regularly playing  at [[Horst Liepolt]]'s ''Jazz Centre 44'' in St Kilda.\n\nLater Buckley teamed with drummer  [[Ted Vining]] and pianist [[Don Wilde]]  with Don Bennett as host to run the [[Cool Cats Show]] on Channel 7 for two years.\n\nFor several years in the early 1960s Buckley dropped out of the Jazz scene to establish Buckley-Hutton laboratories, which would become one of the biggest dental labs in the southern hemisphere, and to devote time to family.\n\nHe emerged in the late sixties teaming up with Brian Brown, Tony Gould and Ted Vining to form the Brian Brown Quartet. After a few years Gould left the group, replaced by a young [[Bob Sedergreen]]. Around 1969 the trio of Buckley, Sedergreen and Vining formed and played together  for the next 37 years. The Quartet disbanded in 1979 when Vining moved north to Sydney then Brisbane.\n\t\nIn the 1980s Buckley joined Martin Jackson (one of the founders of the [[Melbourne Jazz Co-operative]]) in his group Odwala and also participated in Sedergreen's Blues on the Boil, and performed with [[Bernie McGann]].\n\nBuckley's last performance was with the Ted Vining Trio at the North Coast Jazz Festival in Bangalow three months before his death from cancer in September 2006. Three days before his death Buckley donated an historic three-stringed DeVereaux double bass to the Museum of Victoria.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{jazzfooter|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buckley, Barry}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian jazz double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Male double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barry_Buckley"}
